In Microsoft SQL Server, the equivalent data type to C# `datetime` is `datetime`. The `datetime` data type in SQL server stores a date and time value in a field. 

To use `datetime` in a C# application, you can retrieve the value from the database using a `SqlDataReader` object and then cast it to a `DateTime` object using the `GetDateTime` method. 

For example,

```csharp
using (SqlConnection connection = new SqlConnection(connectionString))
{
    SqlCommand command = new SqlCommand("SELECT Date FROM MyTable", connection);
    connection.Open();
    SqlDataReader reader = command.ExecuteReader();
    while (reader.Read())
    {
        DateTime date = reader.GetDateTime(0);
        Console.WriteLine(date);
    }
}
``` 

This code retrieves a `DateTime` value from the `Date` column of the `MyTable` table in the database and writes it to the console.

In Microsoft SQL Server, you can store an array of integer values in a table by creating a separate table to store the integer values (one value per row) and then creating a foreign key relationship to the parent table. 

In C#, you can use a `List<int>` or `int[]` to store an array of integers. To insert the array of integer values into SQL Server, you can either:

1. Loop through the array and execute individual SQL INSERT statements or 
2. Use the `Table Value Parameters` (TVP) feature in SQL Server to insert the array as a single batch using a stored procedure.

Here is an example of using the `DataTable` class to create a TVP in C#:

```csharp
using (SqlConnection connection = new SqlConnection(connectionString))
{
    DataTable table = new DataTable();
    table.Columns.Add("Value", typeof(int));

    int[] values = { 1, 2, 3, 4, 5 };
    foreach (int value in values)
    {
        table.Rows.Add(value);
    }

    SqlCommand command = new SqlCommand("INSERT INTO MyTable (ValueColumn) SELECT Value FROM @Values", connection);
    command.Parameters.AddWithValue("@Values", table);
    connection.Open();
    command.ExecuteNonQuery();
}
```

This code creates a `DataTable` containing the array of integer values and then uses a parameterized `SqlCommand` to insert the values into the `ValueColumn` column of the `MyTable` table.

If you don't want to create a separate table to store the integer array and you want to store the array in a single column of a table, you can use the `varchar` data type to store the array as a comma-separated string. 

In C#, you can use the `string.Join` method to create a comma-separated string from an array of integer values. To retrieve the array of integer values from the database, you can use the `Split` method to split the string into individual values.

Here's an example of how you could insert an array of integer values into an `intArray` column using a parameterized SQL query:

```
using (SqlConnection connection = new SqlConnection(connectionString))
{
    int[] values = { 1, 2, 3, 4, 5 };
    string valueString = string.Join(",", values);

    SqlCommand command = new SqlCommand("INSERT INTO MyTable (intArray) VALUES (@IntArray)", connection);
    command.Parameters.AddWithValue("@IntArray", valueString);
    connection.Open();
    command.ExecuteNonQuery();
}
```

To retrieve the array of integer values from the `intArray` column, you can use the `Split` method to split the string into individual values and then parse each value to an integer:

```
using (SqlConnection connection = new SqlConnection(connectionString))
{
    SqlCommand command = new SqlCommand("SELECT intArray FROM MyTable WHERE Id = @Id", connection);
    command.Parameters.AddWithValue("@Id", 123);
    connection.Open();
    SqlDataReader reader = command.ExecuteReader();
    if (reader.Read())
    {
        string valueString = reader.GetString(0);
        int[] values = valueString.Split(',').Select(int.Parse).ToArray();
        foreach (int value in values)
        {
            Console.WriteLine(value);
        }
    }
}
```

In Microsoft SQL Server, the equivalent data type to a boolean value is `bit`. The `bit` data type is used to store a single bit of binary data, representing either a 0 or 1 value. When you insert a value into a `bit` column, you can use the keywords `0` or `1`, or the literals `false` or `true`.

In C#, the equivalent data type to a boolean value is `bool`. To retrieve a boolean value from a `bit` column in SQL Server in C#, you can use the `SqlDataReader` and the `GetBoolean` method.

Here's an example of how you could insert and retrieve boolean values in a `bit` column using a parameterized SQL query:

```csharp
using (SqlConnection connection = new SqlConnection(connectionString))
{
    bool value = true;

    SqlCommand command = new SqlCommand("INSERT INTO MyTable (boolColumn) VALUES (@BoolValue)", connection);
    command.Parameters.AddWithValue("@BoolValue", value);
    connection.Open();
    command.ExecuteNonQuery();
}

using (SqlConnection connection = new SqlConnection(connectionString))
{
    SqlCommand command = new SqlCommand("SELECT boolColumn FROM MyTable WHERE Id = @Id", connection);
    command.Parameters.AddWithValue("@Id", 123);
    connection.Open();
    SqlDataReader reader = command.ExecuteReader();
    if (reader.Read())
    {
        bool value = reader.GetBoolean(0);
        Console.WriteLine(value);
    }
}
```

This code inserts a boolean value into the `boolColumn` column of the `MyTable` table using a parameterized SQL query and retrieves the boolean value from the column using the `GetBoolean` method of the `SqlDataReader` object.

In Microsoft SQL Server, the equivalent data type to a `byte[]` array in C# is the `varbinary(max)` data type. As the name suggests, `varbinary(max)` allows you to store variable-length binary data up to a maximum size of 2GB per column. 

